            Although it is right that the utilities and the local authorities should be assessed equally on the amount of road congestion they cause, I am not quite sure how that can be done. Will a value for money assessment be made of lane closures and the consequent five-minute traffic jam caused for cars and lorries? Will the assessment apply to cyclists and pedestrians who never suffer such delay because they can get through traffic jams? Worst of all, will the traffic manager&#x2014;who may or may not be a local authority employee&#x2014;have targets for cutting delays?</p><p>
            How will all that work? I can just see it coming. Oxfordshire County Council, for example&#x2014;as I live in Oxford I am using this example&#x2014;will give a contract to Capita, which will make a profit or loss depending on whether it has achieved its targets. The amendment is based on good principles but I can see it snowballing. I think that we have a lot more work to do on the idea.</p><p>
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_68gc' title='Col. 68GC &mdash; HL Deb 27 April 2004 vol 660 c68GC' name='column_68gc' href='#column_68gc' rel='bookmark'>68GC</a>
